<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2013/08/30/webinar-replay-spring-with-cucumber-for-automation">Webinar Replay: Spring with Cucumber for Automation</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon news-and-events"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/news">News and Events</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/c910c2f6520a5977a836d74e86e07cb4?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<span class="author">Pieter Humphrey</span>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2013-08-30 17:45:00.0">August 30, 2013</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="1141" href="/blog/2013/08/30/webinar-replay-spring-with-cucumber-for-automation#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><div>
<p>Learn how Spring and Cucumber integrate to make test automation easier. Cucumber is a framework for Behavior-Driven-Development (BDD), a refinement of TDD (Test-Driven-Development). Its intent is to enable developers to write high-level use cases in plain text that can be verified by non-technical stakeholders, and turn them into executable tests, written in a language called Gherkin. Using Spring, Cucumber, WebDriver2, Hemant Joshi will show you how to use Spring &amp; Cucumber to do BDD with elegance and joy. </p>
<p> </p>
<center>
<iframe width="420" height="315" src="//www.youtube.com/embed/COTnVE1fw5w" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
</center>
<p></p>
</div>
</div>
</section>
